Product description

Elevate Comfort with Heated Floors

Thermostat

Customizable, easy-to-install floor warming accessories for any room

Schlute Programmable Wi-Fi Thermostat for the DITRA-HEAT System

DITRA-HEAT-E-WiFi is a programmable WiFi touchscreen thermostat used to control the DITRA-HEAT-E-HK heating cables (either 120 V or 240 V). The thermostat features a built-in Class A ground fault circuit interrupter (GFCI). DITRA-HEAT-E-WiFi is operated via LCD touchscreen controls and features a pre-set schedule for convenience, which may be programmed to fit any schedule. When connected to WiFi, the thermostat provides convenient monitoring and adjustment of the floor warming system via the web or mobile app. Two heating cables may be connected to the thermostat, up to the total heating load limit of 15 amps. The DITRA-HEAT-E-RR power module may be used in conjunction with the thermostat when the heating load exceeds 15 amps (e.g., in large floor applications) to maintain a single point of control.

How to Install Your Ditra Thermostat

Please refer to the Interactive User Guide and Schluter-DITRA-HEAT Installation Handbook for complete DITRA-HEAT system installation instructions.

1. DITRA-HEAT-E-WiFi must be installed in an electrical box. A single gang, deep electrical box or a double gang electrical box with a single gang mud ring is recommended to provide room for the wiring. The power supply must be shut off and all electrical connections must be made by a qualified electrician, according to the electrical and building codes effective in your region.

2. Connect the heating cable ground braid to the ground wire from the electrical panel. Remove the faceplate from the thermostat power base by loosening the screw and tilting the thermostat upward. Remove the back cover clip as well.

3. For ease of installation, form the electrical line wires into an “M” or accordion shape. This will make it easier to fold them neatly into the electrical box. Loosen the load screws at the top of the thermostat until they stop. Insert the heating cable conductors into the load terminals from the bottom. Since there is no polarity, either heating cable conductor can be connected to either load terminal.

4. Secure the conductors by tightening the screws. Insert the electrical line wires into the line terminals from the top. Refer to the back of thermostat for proper wiring configuration. Secure the wires by tightening the screws and fold the wires into the electrical box.

5. Align and secure the thermostat power base to the electrical box. Thread the floor temperature sensors through the opening at the bottom right of the thermostat power base. Tape up the secondary floor temperature sensor and secure to the power base.

6. Strip the ends of the floor temperature sensor to expose the wires for ease of installation. Insert the floor temperature sensor wires into terminals C and D. Note that the floor temperature sensor wires have no polarity and can be interchanged between C and D terminals. Tighten the screws to secure the wires. The power, heating cable, and floor temperature sensor connections are now complete. Replace the thermostat faceplate and tighten the screw at the bottom of the unit.

Note: Two DITRA-HEAT-E-HK heating cables can be connected and controlled by a single DITRA-HEAT-E-WiFi thermostat if the total current is less than 15 amps. The heating cable leads must be wired in parallel according to applicable electrical and building codes. Multiple DITRA-HEAT-E-HK heating cables over 15 amps cannot be connected to a single DITRA-HEAT-E-WiFi thermostat. Additional DITRA-HEAT-E-WiFi thermostats must be used or the DITRA-HEAT-E-WiFi thermostat may be combined with the DITRA-HEAT-E-RR power modules.

About Us

Always One Step Ahead of the Times!

At Schlüter-Systems, we pride ourselves on being pioneers in the tile assembly industry. Founded in 1966 by Werner Schlüter, we continue to meet the evolving demands of the industry by developing practical and effective solutions for tile installation challenges. Today, Schlüter-Systems' has evolved from a modest idea into a company with over 40 product lines recognized and utilized in various countries around the world, maintaining our commitment to innovation, quality, and service.

  • Can the DITRA-HEAT-E-WIFI be installed to replace an existing Schluter Thermostat or a non-Schluter Thermostat?

    Yes, the Wi-Fi thermostat works with any electric radiant floor heating system under 15 amps. Consult a local electrician to ensure it meets electrical specifications. Only a good Wi-Fi signal and router are needed. Line and load principles apply.

  • What temperature will my heated floor reach?

    Average surface temperature is 75 - 97ºF (24 - 36ºC), but the normal comfortable range is 77 - 84ºF (25 - 29ºC)

One of the symbol button takes you back to regular italics (I made that mistake twice and it makes you start your email input all over again if you mess up). But once you get past that hiccup it was smooth sailing. Schluter sends you to a website (not their main one) once you start the process via an email confirmation. And you can download the iPhone app too. I would recommend once you pair your thermostat onto you wifi, then use use your computer to login from the email they send you, setup your schedule, then download the app on your phone. In that order. I really like once you give it your kWh it can show you how much you spend on a daily, and weekly basis. very nice touch.
    One last thing my old thermostat only went up to 74 F. This one goes up to 80+ F and you can really feel it. For the first time I had ever own this floor heater I had to turn it down. Great upgrade, highly recommended.

  • David M Hollway
    5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    Connections are upside down, really needs a deep wallbox
    Reviewed in the United States on June 10, 2020
    This thermostat works well with the DITRA-Heat system. I have no complaints, but I will offer two observations: Firstly, the connections on the back of the unit for the resistive heating cable and the 120V line feed are upside down. That is, the connections for the... See more
    This thermostat works well with the DITRA-Heat system. I have no complaints, but I will offer two observations:
    Firstly, the connections on the back of the unit for the resistive heating cable and the 120V line feed are upside down. That is, the connections for the floor cable are at the TOP of the unit, and those for the line feed are at the BOTTOM. In my installation, the 120V feed came down from above, meaning that I had to fold both sets of cables to point in the opposite direction before installation. This exacerbated the second issue...

    By the time the line feed, floor cable, and two temp sensor cables are present, there really isn't a lot of room in the wall box. I strongly recommend use of a deep - or double-width? - wallbox with this unit. Which wasn't possible in my case, as my walls are (standard) 2x4" studding, so a standard depth box was all I could use. As a result it's a little tight in there.

    Other than those minor niggles, I'm happy with this. I'll definitely be installing the DITRA Heat system when I remodel the other bathroom in my home.

    1.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    Not impressed. LOUD CLICKS, and not Google/Alexa compatible
    Reviewed in the United States on November 3, 2020
    I'm really disappointed in this thermostat. 1. It makes an incredibly loud click when it turns on. Not good if it's going to be in an echo-ey master bathroom near a bedroom. I wish I'd known this during installation, and I would have installed it in a... See more
    I'm really disappointed in this thermostat.

    1. It makes an incredibly loud click when it turns on. Not good if it's going to be in an echo-ey master bathroom near a bedroom. I wish I'd known this during installation, and I would have installed it in a cabinet or something. Instead, it is in a very prominent location. Frustrating.

    2. It isn't Google Assistant or Alexa compatible. No chance of 'Hey Google, heat the floor." That should be table stakes for a "smart device" in 2020. Disappointing.

    3. The whole thing looks very 2002. It's low res. Low quality. Just not impressive for what should otherwise be a top-shelf heated floor installation. Everything Schluter seems gold plated, and I expected better from the thermostat.

    Bottom line -- it works, but it's pricey and loud, so put it in a cabinet somewhere, and dont expect it to be very "smart."
